Expected presence of sidewalk on roadway.
Not Expected • Urban streets where you do not expect a sidewalk are given a special code (10 or 11) so that they are not flagged as deficient. Examples include freeways, ramps, frontage roads, alleys, median breaks or turn lanes, roundabouts, and private streets in the network that are more like parking lots. This should NOT be used for judgment-based land uses – for instance, a street with sidewalk on one side and a park or cemetery on the other side with no sidewalk should be coded as 1, not 11.
Rural vs Urban • Streets and highways that are generally agricultural, or open space in nature on both sides are rural. • Suburban and exurban subdivisions that typically do not have sidewalk are considered urban, even if they are on well and septic systems. • Roads that have rural cross sections and limited access but have development backing up to them are considered urban. • Partially developed roads (intermittent development, development on one side only, etc.) are considered urban. • Roads that have curb and gutter on at least one side are considered urban. • Urban streets were initially identified as being completely within the 2010 Census urban areas buffered 500 feet, and then manually rationalized, adding Deerfield, Belleview, and Blue Mounds.
Unevaluated • Road may be platted but not built yet, have an upcoming reconstruction project where the addition of sidewalks is unknown, or staff have simply not evaluated the segment yet. New segments and NULLs should default to 9.
